<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-684-957 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 684 957.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  April 25 1991 v17 n9 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>From color lasers to parlor tricks: observers predict what liesahead.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Industry analysts predict a nine percent growth rate for theCanadian computer market over the period of 1991-1995.andP;  Canadacontinues to occupy last place in international computer systemssales among G-7 partners, while the US dominates the $150 billionworld systems market.andP;  In particular technologies, observers seethe NeXT workstations doing better in markets other than Canada,while multimedia technology is viewed as a fad.andP;  In the computerprinter market, color laser printers are expected to dominate asdot-matrix technology fades.andP;  Other areas of development that areexpected to grow include pen-based computing, voice recognitionequipment and image processing as the need for visualizationgrows.andP;  Analysts suggest that vendors pay more attention to useracceptance of new technology, since time-to-market is much slowerthan the ownership cycle.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Industry AnalysisMarket AnalysisGrowthComputer IndustryWorld MarketForecasting.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The 1990 global systems market. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>From color lasers to parlor tricks: observers predict what lies aheadandM;TORONTO -- Canada languishes in last place among G-7 partners when it comesto the global systems market (see chart above) yet a healthy nine per centgrowth is expected domestically in IS spending during the next four years.andM;On the other hand, multimedia is just a &quot;high-tech parlor trick&quot;, the Nextmachine will gather momentum but &quot;somewhere else&quot;, dot matrix printers areout and color laser printers are definitely in.andM;There were those observations and more last month as analysts fromInternational Data Corporation (Canada) Ltd. delivered a pundit's view of1990s-style computing trends.andM;Among the speakers was Aaron Goldberg, vice-president of desktop research forIDC Corp. in Framingham, Mass.andM;&quot;After seven years of incredibly dull sameness there are new technologiesfinally on the horizon,&quot; Goldberg said.andM;They include pen computing, imaging, multimedia and voice recognition.andM;&quot;The use of image to maximize the bandwidth between user and system is goingto be a significant breakthrough,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Some fundamental technologyimprovements as well as the ability for users to visualize the role of imagein their own applications are key.&quot;andM;&quot;Where there's Randamp;D smoke there tends to be product fire.andP;  That is if you putenough Randamp;D efforts into something, products will flow out and eventually beput into a usable format.&quot;andM;Of multimedia as a &quot;parlor trick&quot;, he predicted only the most &quot;rudimentaryimplementation&quot; will come during the next 12 months: &quot;After Apple's abortedrush to market, finding a real role is now critical.&quot;andM;Understandifng end-user patterns is also important, he said.andM;&quot;Our industry is held hostage not by technology trends but by customeracceptance trends.andM;&quot;Product cycles are approaching 12-18 months when the customer-ownershipcycle is 60 months.andP;  You (vendors) better be able to manage that.&quot;andM;An example of distorted acceptance is Microsoft Windows 3.0.andP;  During the past12 months, an estimated six million copies have been sold worldwide.andM;&quot;Correspondingly in that same time time period, the number of Windowsapplications shipped will total 1.2 million,&quot; said Goldberg.andP;  &quot;Now, wait aminute.andP;  Why would somebody buy Windows and not run the Windows apps?&quot;andM;Other speakers included, Paul Kennedy, president of IDC Canada, who said thatthe current recession has &quot;left its mark&quot; on the IT industry.andM;That compares to the early 1980s when vendors escaped with minimal damageduring a downturn in the economy.andO;</TEXT></DOC>